 =20
   =20
      Nothing is securities fraud?
   =20
 =20

The simplest form of fraud is that you lie to someone and they give you mon=
ey. Perhaps you give them something in exchange for their money, but you li=
e about its attributes. (They pay you for magic beans, but the beans are no=
t magic.) Or perhaps you lie about giving them something=C2=A0and give them=
 nothing. (They pay you for the Brooklyn Bridge, but you do not give them t=
he Brooklyn Bridge.) Fraud is=C2=A0often=C2=A0illegal, though exactly how i=
t is illegal will depend on how you do the fraud, and to whom, and what you=
 are lying about.
For instance, doing fraud about securities is illegal under US federal law;=
 this is called securities fraud. Securities fraud often takes the simple f=
orm: You lie to someone (about securities) and they give you money (for the=
 securities). You tell people that you have started a company that has disc=
overed cold fusion, you offer them a 1% stake in the company (stock, a secu=
rity) for $1 million, they pay you, you deliver the stock, but you were lyi=
ng about the cold fusion.
  [1]
=C2=A0This is fairly standard; Elizabeth Holmes and Sam Bankman-Fried are r=
ecent high-profile cases of people=C2=A0convicted of fraud for lying about =
their companies to sell stock to investors.
  [2]

But securities fraud often does=C2=A0not=C2=A0work that way. In modern publ=
ic stock markets, it is possible to=C2=A0lie to people in a way that costs =
them money, and gets you money, without=C2=A0them giving you the money. Sch=
ematically:
=09You have some stock.=09You lie about it.=09The people who believe your l=
ies buy the stock, anonymously, on the stock exchange, so it goes up.=09You=
 sell the stock at a profit, anonymously, on the stock exchange.=09Eventual=
ly your lies are discovered and the stock goes back down again.

You made money (Step 4), and your victims lost money (Step 5), and your lie=
s caused their losses and your gains. But you didn=E2=80=99t necessarily se=
ll the stock=C2=A0to the victims:=C2=A0You sold the stock on the stock exch=
ange, they bought it on the stock exchange, and you have no idea who was on=
 the other side of any of those trades. Quite likely the victims bought the=
 stock from some sophisticated electronic market maker, and you sold the st=
ock to some sophisticated electronic market maker, and the market makers di=
dn=E2=80=99t believe or even see your lies.
This is quite a common form of securities fraud. Companies, for instance, a=
re regularly accused of doing securities fraud for lying about their busine=
ss in a way that keeps their stock price up, even if they are not selling t=
he stock themselves and lying directly to the purchasers. (=E2=80=9CEveryth=
ing is securities fraud,=E2=80=9D I often say.)
But this sort of securities fraud doesn=E2=80=99t have to be done by the co=
mpany. We have talked a few times about fake takeovers, where someone buys =
stock,=C2=A0puts out a fake press release saying that the company will be b=
ought, and then sells the stock at a profit. More broadly,=C2=A0a=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9Cpump and dump=E2=80=9D is a classic form of securities fraud in which=
 someone =E2=80=94=C2=A0perhaps a promoter affiliated with the company, per=
haps just a guy online =E2=80=94=C2=A0buys a stock (often a=C2=A0small, ill=
iquid penny stock) and then tells lies about it. =E2=80=9CThis company disc=
overed cold fusion,=E2=80=9D he says, to his email newsletter subscriber li=
st, or on X or Reddit or whatever. People believe him, they buy the stock, =
the stock goes up (the pump), and he sells his shares (the dump) before the=
 price crashes again. He doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily sell the shares=C2=A0t=
o=C2=A0his email subscribers or X followers, but their buying is what makes=
 his sales profitable.
This is, if you think too hard about it, actually a bit of a puzzle. If you=
 are charged with fraud, you might say: =E2=80=9COh sure I lied about this =
stock, and it went up, and then I sold the stock. But nobody can=C2=A0prove=
=C2=A0that I sold the stock to=C2=A0the people I lied to. So how can I have=
 committed fraud? As far as you know, the people I lied to never gave me mo=
ney, and in fact I never even wanted them to. I just wanted them to buy the=
 stock, so it would go up, so somebody else =E2=80=94=C2=A0some anonymous p=
erson on the stock exchange who never even heard my lies =E2=80=94=C2=A0wou=
ld give me money.=E2=80=9D
I think most people think this is too cute. It sure=C2=A0looks=C2=A0like fr=
aud: You lied, someone believed you, they paid money, a fairly mechanical p=
rocess (the workings of the stock market) occurred, the money came to you. =
Surely that=E2=80=99s fraud. In US securities law, this is called the =E2=
=80=9Cfraud on the market theory.=E2=80=9D In 1988, the Supreme Court endor=
sed the theory
  [3]
:

The fraud on the market theory is based on the hypothesis that, in an open =
and developed securities market, the price of a company=E2=80=99s stock is =
determined by the available material information regarding the company and =
its business. Misleading statements will therefore defraud purchasers of st=
ock even if the purchasers do not directly rely on the misstatements. The c=
ausal connection between the defendants=E2=80=99 fraud and the plaintiffs=
=E2=80=99=C2=A0purchase of stock in such a case is no less significant than=
 in a case of direct reliance on misrepresentations. =E2=80=A6
The modern securities markets, literally involving millions of shares chang=
ing hands daily, differ from the face-to-face transactions contemplated by =
early fraud cases, and our understanding of Rule 10b-5=E2=80=99s reliance r=
equirement must encompass these differences.=C2=A0
In face-to-face transactions, the inquiry into an investor=E2=80=99s relian=
ce upon information is into the subjective pricing of that information by t=
hat investor. With the presence of a market, the market is interposed betwe=
en seller and buyer and, ideally, transmits information to the investor in =
the processed form of a market price. Thus, the market is performing a subs=
tantial part of the valuation process performed by the investor in a face-t=
o-face transaction. The market is acting as the unpaid agent of the investo=
r, informing him that given all the information available to it, the value =
of the stock is worth the market price.

If you lie to=C2=A0the market, and the market believes you and gives you mo=
ney, then that is fraud, even if the particular people who believe you are =
different from the people who give you money.
Or, I mean, that=E2=80=99s what I thought yesterday.=C2=A0
In 2022, federal prosecutors and the US Securities and Exchange Commission =
brought securities fraud charges against a group of people who allegedly di=
d=C2=A0pump and dumps using Twitter, Discord and a podcast. We talked about=
 the case at the time. It was typically silly: The defendants went by onlin=
e nicknames like =E2=80=9CMrZackMorris=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CMystic Mac=E2=
=80=9D and =E2=80=9CThe Stock Sniper,=E2=80=9D the podcast was titled =E2=
=80=9CPennies: Going in Raw,=E2=80=9D the SEC complaint had pictures of a L=
amborghini, and the defendants were publicly saying=C2=A0things like =E2=80=
=9CI=E2=80=99ll never get sick of pumping ... money into my followers bank =
accounts. LETS ALL GET RICH!=E2=80=9D while they were privately saying thin=
gs like =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re robbing f*cking idiots of their money.=E2=80=
=9D
So I couldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0not write about it. But it was kind of boring, r=
eally, just the most garden-variety pump and dump imaginable. =E2=80=9CPret=
ty straightforward fraud,=E2=80=9D I called it. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t kn=
ow why people keep falling for it,=E2=80=9D I wrote. There was nothing part=
icularly novel or interesting about this case except I guess the names.
But yesterday a federal judge in Texas dismissed the criminal charges again=
st MrZackMorris and friends in an absolutely wild opinion ruling that, in f=
act, a pump and dump is not securities fraud, because the people who bought=
 the stock didn=E2=80=99t buy it from the pumpers
  [4]
:
Unlike a traditional fraud case, in which the victim directly surrenders th=
eir property to the defendant (or an entity in the defendant=E2=80=99s cont=
rol), the investors here surrendered their property to the stock market at =
market prices, and in return, received the benefit of the bargain in the fo=
rm of securities. Thus, the scheme did not deprive investors of their money=
 or property through any misrepresentation; the misrepresentations deprived=
 them only of accurate information necessary to make discretionary economic=
 decisions.
And:

There are allegations that the Defendants intended to =E2=80=9Cmaximize=E2=
=80=9D their own trading profits and that Defendants in fact profited from =
their activities. These allegations adequately allege that obtaining financ=
ial gain was an object of the Defendants=E2=80=99 scheme to defraud; obtain=
ing financial gain, however, is only half of the equation. It is the other =
half of the equation =E2=80=94=C2=A0harming a victim=E2=80=99s traditional =
property right =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is lacking.
The Indictment states that =E2=80=9Cthe defendants used their credibility t=
o maximize their own trading profits through their tweets and posts in Atla=
s Trading Discord,=C2=A0often at the expense=C2=A0of their Twitter follower=
s and members of Atlas Trading Discord.=E2=80=9D That allegation, however, =
underscores the issue with the Government=E2=80=99s allegations when accept=
ed as true =E2=80=94=C2=A0the defendants may have =E2=80=9Cused their socia=
l media influence to pump and dump securities for their own financial gain,=
=E2=80=9D but the language of the Indictment indicates that losses to victi=
ms happened incidentally (i.e., =E2=80=9Cat the expense of=E2=80=9D) rather=
 than as the =E2=80=9Cobject of=E2=80=9D the alleged scheme. Rather than pl=
ead a scheme aimed at harming someone=E2=80=99s traditional property right,=
 the scheme as pleaded is totally indifferent to its effect on the alleged =
victims. Many of the alleged victims may have actually made money. This was=
 confirmed at the oral arguments. Moreover, even accepting as true that the=
 alleged victims ultimately lost money on the stock market because the valu=
e of their shares went down, the Defendants did not obtain something of val=
ue from the entity to be deceived. The investors=E2=80=99 trading losses ar=
e one step too far removed from the Defendants=E2=80=99 alleged fraudulent =
misrepresentations.

What a weird opinion. Part of the theory here seems to be that it=E2=80=99s=
 only fraud if you=C2=A0want=C2=A0your victims to lose money, which =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0I mean, then nothing is fraud, is it? Surely everyone=C2=A0who doe=
s a fraud is =E2=80=9Cindifferent to its effect=E2=80=9D on the victims: Th=
e goal is to get money for yourself, not to cost the victims money, though =
of course that is the usual outcome.
  [5]
 If you sell people fake magic beans, you will get money, which is what you=
 want, and they will probably lose money, which you don=E2=80=99t care abou=
t one way or the other. But if=C2=A0they turn around and resell the beans a=
t a profit to some other sucker, you don=E2=80=99t care, and=C2=A0you still=
 did the fraud!
But the main part of the judge=E2=80=99s theory is just that, since the vic=
tims bought stock on the stock market instead of directly from the pump-and=
-dumpers, the pump-and-dumpers could not have been doing fraud on them. Fra=
ud requires a direct connection, a victim=C2=A0who =E2=80=9Cdirectly surren=
ders their property to the defendant.=E2=80=9D And in the public stock mark=
et, where everyone is buying and selling anonymously and probably through m=
arket makers, you can never really prove that the victim traded with the de=
fendant.
Seems wrong to me, but what do I know!
  [6]
=C2=A0If it=E2=80=99s right, though, it means that pump and dumps are compl=
etely legal, as are fake takeover offers
  [7]
: It=E2=80=99s not fraud to lie about stocks=C2=A0and make money trading th=
em, as long as you are only trading on the stock market and not directly wi=
th the people you=E2=80=99re lying to. (Not legal advice! This is one weird=
 opinion in Texas, don=E2=80=99t try it at home.) If that=E2=80=99s right, =
the stock market,=C2=A0and social media, are going to get pretty weird.
  [8]


