      Reddit
   =20
 =20

There is a standard argument, whenever a big tech company does an initial p=
ublic offering, about whether=C2=A0it =E2=80=9Cleft money on the table.=E2=
=80=9D When a company does an IPO, it sells stock to investors at some pric=
e that the company sets with its bankers based on orders from=C2=A0investor=
s, and then the next day the stock opens for trading, and=C2=A0usually=C2=
=A0it trades up. There is an =E2=80=9CIPO pop=E2=80=9D; the stock opens at =
a higher price than what the investors paid the company. The investors who =
bought in the IPO have an instant profit. And then venture capitalists on T=
witter (now X) chime in and say =E2=80=9Cthe company left money on the tabl=
e, why sell stock to investors who could turn around and sell it immediatel=
y at higher prices, why couldn=E2=80=99t the company just sell at those hig=
her prices?=E2=80=9D And they suggest things like direct listings or specia=
l purpose acquisition companies to accomplish that.
There are answers to their question, reasons that the company might decide =
to leave=C2=A0money on the table. The main answer is probably something lik=
e this: The company wants the investors to be happy. If it sells them stock=
 that goes up, and they make a quick profit, they will be happy. This has v=
arious, somewhat fuzzy, long-term advantages for the company. If the invest=
ors are happy, they might support management=E2=80=99s business plans; the =
company will be less vulnerable to activists or hostile takeovers. If the i=
nvestors are happy, and later the company needs to raise more money, maybe =
the investors will buy more stock. If the investors are happy, the stock pr=
ice will go up and=C2=A0keep=C2=A0going up, so that later when the company =
or its pre-IPO investors or its executives want to sell stock, they=E2=80=
=99ll get a better price. Usually a fairly small fraction =E2=80=94=C2=A0sa=
y, 10% to 20% =E2=80=94=C2=A0of the company=E2=80=99s stock is actually sol=
d in the IPO; you want the price to be high when you sell the rest. Happy s=
hareholders make for a higher long-term stock price.
None of these answers are perfect, because markets have short memories and =
the price is driven by fundamentals and supply and demand, not fuzzy invest=
or happiness. If the company=E2=80=99s business performs terribly for two y=
ears after the IPO, and it comes back to the market to raise more money in =
a stock offering, no investor is going to overpay for that stock because th=
ey remember the joy of the IPO pop two years ago. There is nothing=C2=A0rig=
orous=C2=A0about the idea that an IPO pop is good for the company in the lo=
ng term. It just seems, on balance, that treating your investors nicely is =
the sort of thing that might pay off.
One nice thing about Reddit Inc.=E2=80=99s IPO is it makes that argument a =
bit more concrete. Reddit priced its IPO last night at $34 per share, the h=
igh end of the pricing range that it marketed; it raised $748 million in th=
e IPO, on a fully diluted market capitalization of about $6.4 billion. Ther=
e was talk of pricing it=C2=A0above=C2=A0the range: Reddit had enough deman=
d to sell the stock at $35 or $36 or whatever. But it went with $34. As of =
noon today, the stock still had not opened for its first day of trading, so=
 I don=E2=80=99t know if there will be a pop or how big it will be, but the=
 pre-opening indications were around $50 so, probably.
If there is a pop, that will be nice for the institutional investors who bo=
ught in the IPO. But it will also be nice for at least some Reddit users:
About 8% of Reddit=E2=80=99s IPO shares are being set aside for users and m=
oderators who created accounts before Jan. 1, as well as some board members=
 and friends and family of some employees and directors. Those shares won=
=E2=80=99t be subject to a lockup, meaning the owners can sell them on the =
opening day of trading, according to Reddit=E2=80=99s filings.
And the thing is, Reddit is=C2=A0terrified=C2=A0of its users:

Reddit said its millions of loyal users and moderators pose risks as well a=
s a benefit for the company. Redditors have a historically combative relati=
onship with the site, launching revolts over everything from racism on the =
platform to executives=E2=80=99 staffing decisions.
Thousands of members of the WallStreetBets forum =E2=80=94 which boasts aro=
und 15 million users and helped popularize meme stocks like GameStop Corp. =
=E2=80=94 voted to boost a forum post about shorting Reddit=E2=80=99s stock=
 when it begins trading. Their reasons varied from the company=E2=80=99s la=
ck of profitability to competitive concerns.

One reason Reddit sold=C2=A0some of its IPO stock=C2=A0to its users was pro=
bably to buy their loyalty,=C2=A0to cause them to be literally invested in =
Reddit=E2=80=99s success. You sell them stock, and they stick around to com=
ment and moderate and provide value to advertisers and artificial intellige=
nce scrapers. You give them a nice IPO pop, and they are happy. They, you k=
now, vote down the WallStreetBets post about shorting the stock.
That=E2=80=99s a risky move! If you sell them stock at $34 and it=C2=A0goes=
 down, they will be mad at you. They=E2=80=99ll vote up the post about shor=
ting the stock; they=E2=80=99ll be surly and mischievous on their subreddit=
s. Maximizing the price at which you sell the stock is nice, but not=C2=A0t=
hat=C2=A0important in the long run. Making sure that the Redditors who buy =
in the IPO have a good experience is probably more important.

