      Carbon risk transfer
   =20
 =20

I wrote the other day about hypothetical ways that a bank could =E2=80=9Ctr=
ansfer=E2=80=9D its carbon emissions to somebody else. The basic idea is th=
at there are standards =E2=80=94=C2=A0mainly from the Partnership for Carbo=
n Accounting Financials =E2=80=94=C2=A0for calculating the greenhouse gas e=
missions attributable to a bank=E2=80=99s financing activities (that is, lo=
ans that it makes and holds) and its facilitation activities (that is, offe=
rings that it underwrites). Banks face public and regulatory pressure to re=
port low numbers under those standards, but they also want to lend money to=
 oil companies. There is, perhaps, an opportunity for financial engineering=
: Is there a way for a bank to=C2=A0make those loans, but=C2=A0get the emis=
sions off its books=C2=A0for PCAF accounting purposes?
So I wrote about a Bloomberg News story about some hedge funds who have som=
e ideas, and I proposed some crude ideas of my own, but let=E2=80=99s be ho=
nest: My post was mostly a call for financial engineering, a request for my=
 readers to come up with ideas. And of course they did. Reader Andreas Seid=
el suggested a few, of which my favorite might be:
Deflating the emissions by inflating debt. The "base case" PCAF works is by=
 multiplying emissions with the outstanding debt amount and dividing by equ=
ity and debt [I am oversimplifying a little]. If a bank lends $100=C2=A0to =
a company with $50=C2=A0equity and $50=C2=A0other debt, it would get 50% of=
 the emissions. However, what if at the same time, the company borrows a bi=
llion from an off-balance-sheet SPV that invests all the money in money mar=
ket instruments and uses these as collateral and essentially funds itself w=
ith the interest from the money market? Financed emissions drop to practica=
lly zero.=C2=A0
I love the idea of massively grossing up every company=E2=80=99s balance sh=
eet just for carbon-accounting purposes: =E2=80=9CYou can borrow $100 from =
us to build an oil refinery, but only if you also set up a subsidiary that =
borrows $1 billion from a special-purpose vehicle and invests it in money-m=
arket funds, for pure accounting reasons.=E2=80=9D Maybe you could make the=
 economics work, but the accounting=C2=A0for the borrower=C2=A0sure would l=
ook weird.
More generally, one wants some sort of intermediation. Like, a bank that le=
nds money to an oil company is going to have a lot of financed emissions on=
 its books. But what about a bank that lends money to an investment firm na=
med Green Investments Ltd., which then lends it to an oil company? (What if=
 Green Investments is only nominally an investment firm, and really just a =
pass-through vehicle with one asset and one liability =E2=80=94=C2=A0just a=
 way to structure the loan to the oil company?) We have talked about this a=
pproach in the past, as a general way to make oil-company investments seem =
more environmentally friendly (and get them into environmental, social and =
governance investing=C2=A0indexes). I=E2=80=99m not sure it specifically wo=
rks with PCAF standards for banks =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9C=E2=80=98Follow t=
he money=E2=80=99 is a key tenet for GHG accounting of financial assets,=E2=
=80=9D says PCAF, =E2=80=9Cmeaning that the money should be followed as far=
 as possible to understand and account for the climate impact in the real e=
conomy=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I=E2=80=99m sure someone is working on i=
t.

