10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow and next week, back in April.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Nothing is securities fraud?</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The simplest form of fraud is that you lie to =
someone and they give you money. Perhaps you give them something in exchang=
e for their money, but you lie about its attributes. (They pay you for magi=
c beans, but the beans are not magic.) Or perhaps you lie about giving them=
 something=C2=A0and give them nothing. (They pay you for the Brooklyn Bridg=
e, but you do not give them the Brooklyn Bridge.) Fraud is=C2=A0often<em>=
=C2=A0</em>illegal, though exactly how it is illegal will depend on how you=
 do the fraud, and to whom, and what you are lying about.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For instance, doing fraud about securities is =
illegal under <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3476=
8763.286358/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3VzY29kZS90ZXh0LzE4LzEzNDg=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdae0655f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">US federal law</a>; this is cal=
led securities fraud. Securities fraud often takes the simple form: You lie=
 to someone (about securities) and they give you money (for the securities)=
. You tell people that you have started a company that has discovered cold =
fusion, you offer them a 1% stake in the company (stock, a security) for $1=
 million, they pay you, you deliver the stock, but you were lying about the=
 cold fusion.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background=
-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0This is fairly standard; <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/34768763.286358/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3YvdXNhby1uZG=
NhL3ByL3RoZXJhbm9zLWZvdW5kZXItZWxpemFiZXRoLWhvbG1lcy1mb3VuZC1ndWlsdHktaW52Z=
XN0b3ItZnJhdWQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB215c54ff" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Elizabeth Holmes<=
/a> and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34768763.2=
86358/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3YvdXNhby1zZG55L3ByL3VuaXRlZC1zdGF0ZXMtY=
XR0b3JuZXktYW5ub3VuY2VzLWNoYXJnZXMtYWdhaW5zdC1mdHgtZm91bmRlci1zYW11ZWwtYmFu=
a21hbi1mcmllZA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB75e44d11" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Sam Bankman-Fried=
</a> are recent high-profile cases of people=C2=A0convicted of fraud for ly=
ing about their companies to sell stock to investors.<a class=3D"footnote-i=
ndex" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; dis=
play: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But securities fraud often does=C2=A0<em>not=
=C2=A0</em>work that way. In modern public stock markets, it is possible to=
=C2=A0lie to people in a way that<em> costs</em> them money, and <em>gets</=
em> you money, without=C2=A0<em>them giving you the money</em>. Schematical=
ly:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You have some stock.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You lie about it.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">The people who believe your lies buy the stock, anonymously, on th=
e stock exchange, so it goes up.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Y=
ou sell the stock at a profit, anonymously, on the stock exchange.</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Eventually your lies are discovered and th=
e stock goes back down again.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You made money (Step 4), and your victims lost=
 money (Step 5), and your lies caused their losses and your gains. But you =
didn=E2=80=99t necessarily sell the stock=C2=A0<em>to the victims:=C2=A0</e=
m>You sold the stock on the stock exchange, they bought it on the stock exc=
hange, and you have no idea who was on the other side of any of those trade=
s. Quite likely the victims bought the stock from some sophisticated electr=
onic market maker, and you sold the stock to some sophisticated electronic =
market maker, and the market makers didn=E2=80=99t believe or even see your=
 lies.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is quite a common form of securities frau=
d. Companies, for instance, are regularly accused of doing securities fraud=
 for lying about their business in a way that keeps their stock price up, e=
ven if they are not selling the stock themselves and lying directly to the =
purchasers. (=E2=80=9CEverything is securities fraud,=E2=80=9D I often say.=
)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this sort of securities fraud doesn=E2=80=
=99t have to be done by the company. We have talked a few times about <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34768763.286358/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMzAvZmFrZS13ZX=
dvcmstcmVzY3Vlci13YXMtYW4taG91ci1sYXRlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMjEyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJ=
nV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDMyMSZ1=
dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7ae3751f" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
fake takeovers</a>, where someone buys stock,=C2=A0puts out a fake press re=
lease saying that the company will be bought, and then sells the stock at a=
 profit. More broadly,=C2=A0a=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cpump and dump=E2=80=9D is a cla=
ssic form of securities fraud in which someone =E2=80=94=C2=A0perhaps a pro=
moter affiliated with the company, perhaps just a guy online =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0buys a stock (often a=C2=A0small, illiquid penny stock) and then tells l=
ies about it. =E2=80=9CThis company discovered cold fusion,=E2=80=9D he say=
s, to his email newsletter subscriber list, or on X or Reddit or whatever. =
People believe him, they buy the stock, the stock goes up (the pump), and h=
e sells his shares (the dump) before the price crashes again. He doesn=E2=
=80=99t necessarily sell the shares=C2=A0<em>to=C2=A0</em>his email subscri=
bers or X followers, but their buying is what makes his sales profitable.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is, if you think too hard about it, actua=
lly a bit of a puzzle. If you are charged with fraud, you might say: =E2=80=
=9COh sure I lied about this stock, and it went up, and then I sold the sto=
ck. But nobody can=C2=A0<em>prove=C2=A0</em>that I sold the stock to=C2=A0<=
em>the people I lied to</em>. So how can I have committed fraud? As far as =
you know, the people I lied to never gave me money, and in fact I never eve=
n wanted them to. I just wanted them to buy the stock, so it would go up, s=
o somebody else =E2=80=94=C2=A0some anonymous person on the stock exchange =
who never even heard my lies =E2=80=94=C2=A0would give me money.=E2=80=9D</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think most people think this is too cute. It=
 sure=C2=A0<em>looks=C2=A0</em>like fraud: You lied, someone believed you, =
they paid money, a fairly mechanical process (the workings of the stock mar=
ket) occurred, the money came to you. Surely that=E2=80=99s fraud. In US se=
curities law, this is called the =E2=80=9Cfraud on the market theory.=E2=80=
=9D In 1988, the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
4768763.286358/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdXByZW1lLmp1c3RpYS5jb20vY2FzZXMvZmVkZXJhbC91cy80=
ODUvMjI0Lw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB64d8b873" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Supreme Court endorse=
d</a> the theory<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgro=
und-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The fraud on the market theory is based on the=
 hypothesis that, in an open and developed securities market, the price of =
a company=E2=80=99s stock is determined by the available material informati=
on regarding the company and its business. Misleading statements will there=
fore defraud purchasers of stock even if the purchasers do not directly rel=
y on the misstatements. The causal connection between the defendants=E2=80=
=99 fraud and the plaintiffs=E2=80=99=C2=A0purchase of stock in such a case=
 is no less significant than in a case of direct reliance on misrepresentat=
ions. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The modern securities markets, literally invol=
ving millions of shares changing hands daily, differ from the face-to-face =
transactions contemplated by early fraud cases, and our understanding of Ru=
le 10b-5=E2=80=99s reliance requirement must encompass these differences.=
=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In face-to-face transactions, the inquiry into=
 an investor=E2=80=99s reliance upon information is into the subjective pri=
cing of that information by that investor. With the presence of a market, t=
he market is interposed between seller and buyer and, ideally, transmits in=
formation to the investor in the processed form of a market price. Thus, th=
e market is performing a substantial part of the valuation process performe=
d by the investor in a face-to-face transaction. The market is acting as th=
e unpaid agent of the investor, informing him that given all the informatio=
n available to it, the value of the stock is worth the market price.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you lie to=C2=A0<em>the market</em>, and th=
e market believes you and gives you money, then that is fraud, even if the =
particular people who believe you are different from the people who give yo=
u money.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or, I mean, that=E2=80=99s what I thought yest=
erday.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2022, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/34768763.286358/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3Yvb3BhL3B=
yL2VpZ2h0LW1lbi1pbmRpY3RlZC0xMTQtbWlsbGlvbi1zZWN1cml0aWVzLWZyYXVkLXNjaGVtZS=
1vcmNoZXN0cmF0ZWQtdGhyb3VnaC1zb2NpYWwtbWVkaWE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa565=
fb03" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">federal prosecutors</a> and the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/34768763.286358/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXd=
zL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMi0yMjE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0a53d2cd" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>US Securities and Exchange Commission</a> brought securities fraud charges=
 against a group of people who allegedly did=C2=A0pump and dumps using Twit=
ter, Discord and a podcast. We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/34768763.286358/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTItMTQvc3RvY2stc25pcGVyLW1pZ2h0LWhhdmUtcHVtcGVkLWFuZC1kd=
W1wZWQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMyMTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291=
cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMzIxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe1650ce2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">talked about the case at the time<=
/a>. It was typically silly: The defendants went by online nicknames like =
=E2=80=9CMrZackMorris=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CMystic Mac=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=
=9CThe Stock Sniper,=E2=80=9D the podcast was titled =E2=80=9CPennies: Goin=
g in Raw,=E2=80=9D the SEC complaint had pictures of a Lamborghini, and the=
 defendants were publicly saying=C2=A0things like =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll nev=
er get sick of pumping ... money into my followers bank accounts. LETS ALL =
GET RICH!=E2=80=9D while they were privately saying things like =E2=80=9CWe=
=E2=80=99re robbing f*cking idiots of their money.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So I couldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>not </em>write =
about it. But it was kind of boring, really, just the most garden-variety p=
ump and dump imaginable. =E2=80=9CPretty straightforward fraud,=E2=80=9D I =
called it. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t know why people keep falling for it,=E2=
=80=9D I wrote. There was nothing particularly novel or interesting about t=
his case except I guess the names.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But yesterday a federal judge in Texas dismiss=
ed the criminal charges against MrZackMorris and friends in an <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34768763.286358/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3=
NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JtTU9nUFFnb3pJdy92M=
A/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb8c2dc7b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">absolutely wild opinion</a> ru=
ling that, in fact, a pump and dump is not securities fraud, because the pe=
ople who bought the stock didn=E2=80=99t buy it from the pumpers<a class=3D=
"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !imp=
ortant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Unlike a traditional fraud case, i=
n which the victim directly surrenders their property to the defendant (or =
an entity in the defendant=E2=80=99s control), the investors here surrender=
ed their property to the stock market at market prices, and in return, rece=
ived the benefit of the bargain in the form of securities. Thus, the scheme=
 did not deprive investors of their money or property through any misrepres=
entation; the misrepresentations deprived them only of accurate information=
 necessary to make discretionary economic decisions.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are allegations that the Defendants inte=
nded to =E2=80=9Cmaximize=E2=80=9D their own trading profits and that Defen=
dants in fact profited from their activities. These allegations adequately =
allege that obtaining financial gain was an object of the Defendants=E2=80=
=99 scheme to defraud; obtaining financial gain, however, is only half of t=
he equation. It is the other half of the equation =E2=80=94=C2=A0harming a =
victim=E2=80=99s traditional property right =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is lacking.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Indictment states that =E2=80=9Cthe defend=
ants used their credibility to maximize their own trading profits through t=
heir tweets and posts in Atlas Trading Discord,=C2=A0<em>often at the expen=
se=C2=A0</em>of their Twitter followers and members of Atlas Trading Discor=
d.=E2=80=9D That allegation, however, underscores the issue with the Govern=
ment=E2=80=99s allegations when accepted as true =E2=80=94=C2=A0the defenda=
nts may have =E2=80=9Cused their social media influence to pump and dump se=
curities for their own financial gain,=E2=80=9D but the language of the Ind=
ictment indicates that losses to victims happened incidentally (i.e., =E2=
=80=9Cat the expense of=E2=80=9D) rather than as the =E2=80=9Cobject of=E2=
=80=9D the alleged scheme. Rather than plead a scheme aimed at harming some=
one=E2=80=99s traditional property right, the scheme as pleaded is totally =
indifferent to its effect on the alleged victims. Many of the alleged victi=
ms may have actually made money. This was confirmed at the oral arguments. =
Moreover, even accepting as true that the alleged victims ultimately lost m=
oney on the stock market because the value of their shares went down, the D=
efendants did not obtain something of value from the entity to be deceived.=
 The investors=E2=80=99 trading losses are one step too far removed from th=
e Defendants=E2=80=99 alleged fraudulent misrepresentations.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What a weird opinion. Part of the theory here =
seems to be that it=E2=80=99s only fraud if you=C2=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>you=
r victims to lose money, which =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I mean, then nothing is fraud=
, is it? Surely <em>everyone=C2=A0</em>who does a fraud is =E2=80=9Cindiffe=
rent to its effect=E2=80=9D on the victims: The goal is to get money for yo=
urself, not to cost the victims money, though of course that is the usual o=
utcome.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #00=
0000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color=
: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a> If you sell people fake magic beans, you will get money, which is what=
 you want, and they will probably lose money, which you don=E2=80=99t care =
about one way or the other. But if=C2=A0they turn around and resell the bea=
ns at a profit to some other sucker, you don=E2=80=99t care, and=C2=A0you s=
till did the fraud!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the main part of the judge=E2=80=99s theor=
y is just that, since the victims bought stock on the stock market instead =
of directly from the pump-and-dumpers, the pump-and-dumpers could not have =
been doing fraud on them. Fraud requires a direct connection, a victim=C2=
=A0who =E2=80=9Cdirectly surrenders their property to the defendant.=E2=80=
=9D And in the public stock market, where everyone is buying and selling an=
onymously and probably through market makers, you can never really prove th=
at the victim traded with the defendant.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Seems wrong to me, but what do I know!<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0If it=E2=80=99s right, though, it means that pump and dumps are c=
ompletely legal, as are fake takeover offers<a class=3D"footnote-index" hre=
f=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inl=
ine-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>: It=E2=80=99s not fraud to lie about stocks=C2=A0and make money tradin=
g them, as long as you are only trading on the stock market and not directl=
y with the people you=E2=80=99re lying to. (Not legal advice! This is one w=
eird opinion in Texas, don=E2=80=99t try it at home.) If that=E2=80=99s rig=
ht, the stock market,=C2=A0and social media, are going to get pretty weird.=
<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-8" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: trans=
parent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a></p>
