z9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzIxMjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9=
bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAzMjEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB2f0b7fab" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">wrote the other day</a> about hypotheti=
cal ways that a bank could =E2=80=9Ctransfer=E2=80=9D its carbon emissions =
to somebody else. The basic idea is that there are standards =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0mainly from the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/34768763.286358/aHR0cHM6Ly9jYXJib25hY2NvdW50aW5nZmluYW5jaWFscy5jb20vZW4vc3=
RhbmRhcmQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7f2b50f6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Partnership for Carbon=
 Accounting Financials</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0for calculating the greenhouse ga=
s emissions attributable to a bank=E2=80=99s financing activities (that is,=
 loans that it makes and holds) and its facilitation activities (that is, o=
fferings that it underwrites). Banks face public and regulatory pressure to=
 report low numbers under those standards, but they also want to lend money=
 to oil companies. There is, perhaps, an opportunity for financial engineer=
ing: Is there a way for a bank to=C2=A0<em>make those loans</em>, but=C2=A0=
<em>get the emissions off its books=C2=A0</em>for PCAF accounting purposes?=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So I wrote about a Bloomberg News story about =
some hedge funds who have some ideas, and I proposed some crude ideas of my=
 own, but let=E2=80=99s be honest: My post was mostly a call for financial =
engineering, a request for my readers to come up with ideas. And of course =
they did. Reader Andreas Seidel suggested a few, of which my favorite might=
 be:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Deflating the emissions by inflati=
ng debt. The "base case" PCAF works is by multiplying emissions with the ou=
tstanding debt amount and dividing by equity and debt [I am oversimplifying=
 a little]. If a bank lends $100=C2=A0to a company with $50=C2=A0equity and=
 $50=C2=A0other debt, it would get 50% of the emissions. However, what if a=
t the same time, the company borrows a billion from an off-balance-sheet SP=
V that invests all the money in money market instruments and uses these as =
collateral and essentially funds itself with the interest from the money ma=
rket? Financed emissions drop to practically zero.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I love the idea of massively grossing up every=
 company=E2=80=99s balance sheet just for carbon-accounting purposes: =E2=
=80=9CYou can borrow $100 from us to build an oil refinery, but only if you=
 also set up a subsidiary that borrows $1 billion from a special-purpose ve=
hicle and invests it in money-market funds, for pure accounting reasons.=E2=
=80=9D Maybe you could make the economics work, but the accounting=C2=A0<em=
>for the borrower=C2=A0</em>sure would look weird.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More generally, one wants some sort of interme=
diation. Like, a bank that lends money to an oil company is going to have a=
 lot of financed emissions on its books. But what about a bank that lends m=
oney to an investment firm named Green Investments Ltd., which then lends i=
t to an oil company? (What if Green Investments is only nominally an invest=
ment firm, and really just a pass-through vehicle with one asset and one li=
ability =E2=80=94=C2=A0just a way to structure the loan to the oil company?=
) We have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34768763=
.286358/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDc=
tMTIvaXQtcy1lYXN5LXRvLW1ha2Utb2lsLWNvbXBhbmllcy1lc2c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMyMTI0X0=
1PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlc=
m09MjQwMzIxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc6cf10=
d8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">talked about this approach</a> in the past, as a general way t=
o make oil-company investments seem more environmentally friendly (and get =
them into environmental, social and governance investing=C2=A0indexes). I=
=E2=80=99m not sure it specifically works with PCAF standards for banks =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9C=E2=80=98Follow the money=E2=80=99 is a key tenet for =
GHG accounting of financial assets,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/34768763.286358/aHR0cHM6Ly9jYXJib25hY2NvdW50aW5n=
ZmluYW5jaWFscy5jb20vZmlsZXMvZG93bmxvYWRzL1BDQUYtR2xvYmFsLUdIRy1TdGFuZGFyZC5=
wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB81b650bc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">says PCAF</a>, =E2=80=9Cmea=
ning that the money should be followed as far as possible to understand and=
 account for the climate impact in the real economy=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but I=E2=80=99m sure someone is working on it.</p>
