ions by lower courts, and I have omitted the internal quotation marks and e=
llipses.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-4" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[4] I omit citations in the quotations from th=
e opinion.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-5" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[5] For instance, I am *certain* that Sam Bank=
man-Fried and Elizabeth Holmes did not *want* their investors or customers =
to lose money. Why would they *want* that? It just seems irrelevant to the =
question of whether they did fraud.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-6" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[6] The judge=E2=80=99s theory here comes from=
 a 2023 US Supreme Court decision called <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/34768763.286358/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2NvdHVzYmxvZy5jb20v=
Y2FzZS1maWxlcy9jYXNlcy9jaW1pbmVsbGktdi11bml0ZWQtc3RhdGVzLw/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB4b147f9c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">Ciminelli v. United States</a>. In that case, a =
contractor bribed public officials to get a $750 million city contract and =
was convicted of wire fraud. The Supreme Court reversed his conviction, rul=
ing that it is not wire fraud to =E2=80=9Cto deprive the victim of =E2=80=
=98potentially valuable economic information=E2=80=99 =E2=80=98necessary to=
 make discretionary economic decisions.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34768763.286358/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc3V=
wcmVtZWNvdXJ0Lmdvdi9vcGluaW9ucy8yMnBkZi8yMS0xMTcwX2I5N2QucGRm/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cBb735d574" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">The opinion</a> is a little puzzling: It does=
n=E2=80=99t quite say that bribing public officials to win city contracts i=
sn=E2=80=99t wire fraud, only that the prosecution=E2=80=99s theory for why=
 it was wire fraud was wrong. For a long time, US prosecutors argued that b=
ribes were wire fraud because they deprived the government of the =E2=80=9C=
honest services=E2=80=9D of its officials, but the Supreme Court eventually=
 concluded that that=E2=80=99s not fraud, only depriving victims of money i=
s fraud. The =E2=80=9Cpotentially valuable economic information=E2=80=9D th=
eory looks to the Supreme Court too much like =E2=80=9Chonest services,=E2=
=80=9D so it reversed the convictions. It seems to me like =E2=80=9Cwe tric=
ked the government into giving us a $750 million construction contract=E2=
=80=9D looks a lot like taking money from the government, but for some reas=
on that theory was not at issue in the case. (See <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34768763.286358/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc3VwcmVtZWN=
vdXJ0Lmdvdi9vcGluaW9ucy8yMnBkZi8yMS0xMTcwX2I5N2QucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cCb735d574" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">footnote 1</a>: =E2=80=9CAn earlier indictment allege=
d that the Buffalo Billion contracts were the property at issue. But, to de=
fend against the defendants=E2=80=99 motion to dismiss, the Government reli=
ed solely on the theory that the scheme 'defraud[ed] Fort Schuyler of its r=
ight to control its assets.' =E2=80=A6 The District Court then relied expre=
ssly on the right-to-control theory in denying the motion to dismiss.=E2=80=
=9D) Anyway, the application of this theory to pump and dump scams makes ab=
solutely no sense to me but here we are.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-7" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[7] The interesting question is: Does this mak=
e *insider trading* legal? </p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-8" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[8] Also crypto, I guess, though how much weir=
der can that get.</p>
</div>
